----------------------------------------------------------------
1. TRANSPORT PRINCIPLE
----------------------------------------------------------------

Consider a cumulative response system in which the loading density
m(r) depends on the overlap between baryonic and realised gravity:

    m(r) ∝ [ g_b(r) g_obs(r) ]^(1/(p-1))

Define the cumulative stiffness coordinate

    u(r) = ∫_0^r m(s) ds.

In galaxy outer regions

    g_b(r) ~ r^(-2)
    g_obs(r) ~ r^(-1)

so

    g_b g_obs ~ r^(-3)

and

    m(r) ~ r^(-3/(p-1)).

Thus

    u(r) ~ ∫ r^(-3/(p-1)) dr.

----------------------------------------------------------------
Theorem (Marginal Cumulative Transport)

The cumulative coordinate grows logarithmically

    u(r) ~ log r

if and only if

    3/(p-1) = 1  →  p = 4.

Thus quartic transport uniquely produces marginal accumulation:

    m(r) ∝ (g_b g_obs)^(1/3).

For p < 4 loading converges; for p > 4 it diverges as a power law.
Hence p = 4 is the unique marginal case. ∎


----------------------------------------------------------------
2. COVARIANT CURVATURE–MEMORY FIELD
----------------------------------------------------------------

Introduce a scalar memory field

    M(x)

representing the local amplitude of retained curvature loading.

In the galaxy regime

    m(r) ~ M(r).


----------------------------------------------------------------
2.1 Covariant Action

The minimal toy Lagrangian is

    L = √(-g) [
        1/2 ∇_μ M ∇^μ M
        − (a/4) M^4
        + b Π M
    ].

where

    a = quartic self-interaction
    b = source coupling
    Π = curvature overlap invariant.


----------------------------------------------------------------
2.2 Source–Response Overlap

Define

    Π = sqrt[(∇_μ Φ_b ∇^μ Φ_b)(a_ν a^ν)]

where

    Φ_b = baryonic gravitational potential
    a_μ = four-acceleration of static observers.

In the weak-field limit

    |∇Φ_b| → g_b
    sqrt(a_μ a^μ) → g_obs

so

    Π → g_b g_obs.


----------------------------------------------------------------
2.3 Field Equation

Variation gives

    □M + a M^3 = b Π.

In quasi-static galaxies

    □M << a M^3

so

    M^3 ≈ (b/a) Π.

Thus

    M ∝ (g_b g_obs)^(1/3).


----------------------------------------------------------------
3. STATIC SPHERICAL GALAXY EQUATION
----------------------------------------------------------------

For M = M(r)

    (1/r²)(r² M')' + a M³ = b Π(r)

and in galaxies

    Π(r) ≈ g_b(r) g_obs(r).


----------------------------------------------------------------
3.1 Outer-Galaxy Solution

With

    g_b ~ GM_b / r²
    g_obs ~ V∞² / r

we obtain

    Π ~ r^(-3).

The asymptotic solution becomes

    M(r) = K / r

with

    K = [(b/a) GM_b V∞²]^(1/3).

This profile exactly satisfies the field equation since

    (r² M')' = 0.


----------------------------------------------------------------
4. CUMULATIVE STIFFNESS COORDINATE
----------------------------------------------------------------

Define

    u(r) = ∫_0^r M(s) ds.

Using the outer solution

    M ~ 1/r

gives

    u(r) ~ K log r.

Thus galaxy dynamics occur in a logarithmically expanding
source coordinate.


----------------------------------------------------------------
5. RESPONSE LAW
----------------------------------------------------------------

Define the normalized response field

    S(r) = u(r) / u(R_s).

The rotation curve follows

    V(r)/V∞ = 1 − exp[−S(r)].

This produces the observed stretched master curve.


----------------------------------------------------------------
6. IMPLICIT RADIAL ACCELERATION RELATION
----------------------------------------------------------------

Transport implies

    u'(r) = C [g_b(r) g_obs(r)]^(1/3).

With

    S = u/u_s

and

    g_obs(r) = V∞² / r (1 − e^{-S})²

the differential equation becomes

    dS/dr =
    A V∞^(2/3) r^(-1/3) g_b(r)^(1/3) (1 − e^{-S})^(2/3)

where

    A = C/u_s.

Separating variables yields

    F(S(r)) =
    A V∞^(2/3) ∫_0^r s^(-1/3) g_b(s)^(1/3) ds

with

    F(S) = ∫_0^S dσ / (1 − e^{-σ})^(2/3).

Observed acceleration is

    g_obs = V∞² / r (1 − e^{-S})².


----------------------------------------------------------------
6.1 Weak-Response Limit

For

    S << 1

    F(S) ≈ 3 S^(1/3)

which gives locally

    g_obs ∝ g_b^(2 − 3/q)

if

    g_b ~ r^(-q).


----------------------------------------------------------------
7. BARYONIC TULLY–FISHER RELATION
----------------------------------------------------------------

At large radius

    M(r) ~ (GM_b V∞²)^(1/3) / r.

The cumulative coordinate at the turnover radius becomes

    u(R_s) ~ (GM_b V∞²)^(1/3) Λ_s

where Λ_s is a weak logarithmic structural factor.

If galaxies reach a common saturation condition

    S(R_s) = 1

then

    u(R_s) ≈ const.

Hence

    (GM_b V∞²)^(1/3) ≈ const

which implies

    V∞⁴ ∝ GM_b.

Thus the BTFR emerges from saturation of cumulative transport.


----------------------------------------------------------------
8. FRW COSMOLOGY OF THE MEMORY FIELD
----------------------------------------------------------------

In a homogeneous universe

    M = M(t)

and the field equation becomes

    M̈ + 3H Ṁ + a M³ = b Π.

In FRW the overlap vanishes to leading order

    Π ≈ 0

so

    M̈ + 3H Ṁ + a M³ = 0.


----------------------------------------------------------------
8.1 Energy Density

The scalar contributes

    ρ_M = ½ Ṁ² + aM⁴/4
    p_M = ½ Ṁ² − aM⁴/4.


----------------------------------------------------------------
8.2 Friedmann Equations

    H² = (8πG/3)(ρ_b + ρ_M)

    Ḣ = −4πG(ρ_b + p_b + ρ_M + p_M).


----------------------------------------------------------------
8.3 Scaling Behaviour

For quartic potential

    V(M) = aM⁴/4

the oscillatory equation of state is

    w = 1/3.

Thus

    ρ_M ∝ a^{-4}

and the field behaves like radiation.


----------------------------------------------------------------
9. COSMOLOGY–GALAXY MATCHING
----------------------------------------------------------------

Let the homogeneous cosmological amplitude be

    M_bg.

Galaxy transport becomes nonlinear when

    g_b g_obs ~ (a/b) M_bg³.

Define the galaxy acceleration scale

    g†² ~ (a/b) M_bg³.

Thus

    g† ~ (a/b)^{1/2} M_bg^{3/2}.


----------------------------------------------------------------
9.1 Cosmological Scale of the Field

Balancing Hubble damping and the quartic potential gives

    M_bg² ~ H²/a

so

    M_bg ~ H / √a.


----------------------------------------------------------------
9.2 Resulting Acceleration Scale

Substituting gives

    g†² ~ H³ / (b √a)

or approximately

    g† ~ c H / √(b √a).

Thus the galaxy acceleration scale is naturally of order

    g† ~ c H₀.

This connects galaxy dynamics to the cosmological expansion rate.


